---
/** Hub: rental income tax. Worked example by rentalIncome(). */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import RentalIncomeCalculator from '../../components/calculators/RentalIncomeCalculator.tsx';
import { rentalIncome } from '../../lib/rental';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = rentalIncome(48000, 275000, 12000, 4500, 1800, 3000, 0, 80000, 'single', 'OH', false);
---

<Base
  title="Rental income tax calculator 2026 — Schedule E or C"
  description="Tax on rental income: gross rent less mortgage interest, property tax, depreciation and expenses. Schedule E (no SE tax) or Schedule C for services."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Rental income tax calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Depreciation is the deduction that makes rental income look larger on paper than it costs in tax.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Rental income is taxed on the profit, not the rent. Mortgage interest, property
    tax, insurance, repairs, and — quietly the largest — depreciation all come off
    first. A simple rental is Schedule E with no self-employment tax; a short-term
    rental where you provide substantial services (an Airbnb with cleaning and
    concierge) is Schedule C and owes SE tax. This works out both.
  </p>

  <RentalIncomeCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example — {formatMoney(48000)} of rent</h2>
  <p>
    A landlord collects {formatMoney(48000)} on a property with a {formatMoney(275000)}
    building basis, and {formatMoney(80000)} of other income:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Line</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Gross rent</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.grossRent)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Depreciation (basis ÷ 27.5)</td><td>− {formatMoney(ex.depreciation)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Total expenses incl. depreciation</td><td>− {formatMoney(ex.totalExpenses)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Net rental income</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.netIncome)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Income tax on the rental</td><td>− {formatMoney(ex.incomeTax + ex.stateTax)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>After-tax rental income</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.afterTax)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The {formatMoney(10000)} of depreciation shelters that much rent from tax without
    costing a dollar of cash — which is why real estate is tax-favored. But it is
    recaptured (taxed) when you sell, so it is a deferral, not a free lunch. On
    Schedule E there is no self-employment tax; the {formatMoney(ex.netIncome)} of
    profit is taxed at ordinary rates only.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How is rental income taxed?</h3>
    <p>
      On net profit — rent minus deductible expenses and depreciation — at your
      ordinary income rate. Most rentals are Schedule E, which is not subject to the
      15.3% self-employment tax. That is a major advantage over active
      self-employment income.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What is depreciation and why does it matter?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      You deduct the building's cost (not the land) over 27.5 years for residential
      rental property — about 3.6% a year. It offsets rent you actually received, so
      a cash-flow-positive rental can show little or no taxable income. It is
      recaptured at up to 25% when you sell, so plan for that.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>When is a rental Schedule C instead of Schedule E?</h3>
    <p>
      When you provide substantial services beyond basic rental — daily cleaning,
      meals, a concierge — as some short-term Airbnb-style rentals do. Then it is a
      business on Schedule C and owes self-employment tax on the profit. A plain
      long-term lease is almost always Schedule E.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Can I deduct a rental loss?</h3>
    <p>
      Sometimes. Rental losses are passive and generally offset only passive income —
      but there is a special allowance of up to {formatMoney(25000)} for active
      participants below an income limit, and real-estate professionals are exempt
      from the passive rules. Disallowed losses carry forward.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/rental-host-tax-calculator/">Rental host tax calculator</a> — by platform</li>
    <li><a href="/capital-gains-tax-calculator/">Capital gains calculator</a> — selling the property</li>
    <li><a href="/1099-tax-calculator/">1099 tax calculator</a> — for Schedule C rentals</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Estimate for the 2026 tax year. Depreciation recapture and passive-loss limits
    apply on sale and at a loss. Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
